AGI - The diplomatic advisor of the Kremlin, Yuri Ushakov, said that Russia, concerning the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-03-13/cremlino-su-tregua-in-ucraine-un-we-no-one-position-30414707/"> a temporary agreement in Ukraine</a>, "does not want a He added that the temporary ceasefire proposed is "nothing but a momentary truce to allow the Ukrainian army to recover", stressing that "measures that imitate peaceful actions in Ukraine do not serve anyone". Ushakov also stated that President Vladimir Putin will express the Moscow position on the initiative of a ceasefire of 30 days in Ukraine during a press conference scheduled for today, after talks with his Belarusian counterpart, Aleksander Lukashenko. He pointed out that, during the conference, the presidents will answer questions and Putin will provide more specific and substantial assessments of the question.
Ushakov also underlined that the Kremlin expects the United States to "take into account the Russian position in the future joint work," pointing out that between the two countries there is a "normal exchange of views" and that the United States is aware that "the accession of Ukraine to NATO is out of question". Words expressed on television on the day the Washington Special Envoy arrived in Moscow for talks, Steve Witkoff.
The spokesman of the Russian Foreign Ministry, Maria Zakharova, commented on the statements of some European politicians, including Ursula von der Leyen, according to which "the ball is in the field of Russia" for the solution of the conflict in Ukraine, defining her an attempt to "distorte the reality" > and to avoid recognizing that they are Europeans to have "stretched the stake". He added that these statements represent "another inappropriate way to form a distorted view of the situation", criticizing European policies which, in his opinion, contribute to the escalation of the conflict.
New attacks on Mattarella
The statements by Italian President Sergio Mattarella that Russia is threatening Europe with nuclear weapons are "goods and misinformation". He said this during a briefing the spokesman of the Russian Foreign Ministry, Maria Zakharova, as the agency Tass reports. "You may well ask the President of the Italian Republic for what reasons he was allowed to lie like that. Perhaps you will be worthy to confirm your words somehow?", the spokesman continued. "But I can tell you right away: you can't.> He will not find a single statement of any official of the Russian Federation who can be interpreted this way," he added.
"The Russian leadership, the president of our country, the authorized ministers, government officials have repeatedly pronounced themselves on this subject and have done everything to deny such fakes," said Zakharova. "I am surprised that perhaps the president of Italy has confused us with some other country, perhaps he meant that it is France to threaten Europe with nuclear weapons? Because that's exactly how we could interpret the statements made by the President of France when he discussed the issue of opening a nuclear umbrella on Europe," he concluded.&nbsp;
&nbsp; The new Kremlin attack comes after the speech given by the head of the state during his official visit to Japan ended this Monday. Meeting with Hiroshima last Friday, the leaders of Nihon Hidankyo, the association of survivors of nuclear bombs, Mattarella had launched a sharp appeal against the use of nuclear in conflicts > and, in particular, against the Russian Federation "promoting a renewed and dangerous nuclear narrative" which still instills "the unacceptable idea that nuclear devices could inevitably become an ordinary instrument in the management of nuclear weapons".
In the same speech Mattarella had also pointed his finger against the 'disinvolvement' of the Moscow attitude whose threats to resort to nuclear devices "are pronounced with disturbing recklessness" even when "the destinies of humanity are at stake". In Hiroshima, as well as in the previous stages of his Japanese trip, Mattarella had reiterated the "firm condemnation" of the Italian Republic of these "dangerous drifts".
